model_details.name: Using Convolutional Neural Networks to Classify Hate-Speech
model_details.overview: In this experiment, different implementations of Convolutional Neural Networls are evaluated.
model_details.documentation:
The paper introduces a deep learningbased Twitter hate-speech text classification system. The classifier assigns each
tweet to one of four predefined categories:
racism, sexism, both (racism and sexism) and non-hate-speech. Four Convolutional Neural Network models were
trained on resp. character 4-grams, word
vectors based on semantic information
built using word2vec, randomly generated
word vectors, and word vectors combined
with character n-grams. The feature set
was down-sized in the networks by maxpooling, and a softmax function used to
classify tweets. Tested by 10-fold crossvalidation, the model based on word2vec
embeddings performed best, with higher
precision than recall, and a 78.3% F-score

tradeoffs.description:
"In particular, the system was not able to identify
properly the category ‘both’, since the examples
of this category are very few (1 or 2 per fold) with
respect to the whole set of training instances"
